multiple_choice_question.text: A fragment F of set theory is dichotomic if...
choices: ...it admits only finite models.
...it admits only infinite models.
...there exists a map f: ω→ω such that for every formula φ ∈ F admitting only finite models and for every set assignment M, we have M⊨φ⇒rk(dom(M))<f(|Vars(φ)|).
...none of the above.

multiple_choice_question.text: Which of the following is true about the theory MLSP?
choices: MLSP is not a fragment of set theory.
MLSP is dichotomic.
MLSP is not dichotomic.
The dichotomic nature of MLSP has not been determined.

multiple_choice_question.text: Which of the following is true about the theory MLSCNOTORD?
choices: MLSCNOTORD is dichotomic.
MLSCNOTORD is not dichotomic.
MLSCNOTORD is a subset of MLSP.
The dichotomic nature of MLSCNOTORD has not been determined.

multiple_choice_question.text: What is the consequence of MLSCNOTORD not being dichotomic?
choices: MLSCNOTORD with disjoint unary union is decidable.
MLSCNOTORD with disjoint unary union is undecidable.
MLSCNOTORD is equivalent to MLSP.
There are no consequences.

multiple_choice_question.text: What does Lemma 4.1 state about the singleton operator?
choices: The singleton operator is not expressible in MLSC.
The singleton operator is expressible in MLSC.
The singleton operator is equivalent to the powerset operator.
None of the above.
